00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Downloaded From www.AllSubs.org

1
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:12,300
On the other side
of the world...

2
00:01:12,330 --> 00:01:15,960
in Europe the Allied forces
are pounding the Germans...

3
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:17,800
with relentless force.

4
00:01:17,840 --> 00:01:21,640
We do not expect to have
a winter lull in Europe.

5
00:01:21,680 --> 00:01:23,970
We expect to
keep striking...

6
00:01:24,010 --> 00:01:25,640
to keep the enemy
on the move...

7
00:01:25,680 --> 00:01:27,150
and hit him again
and again.

8
00:01:27,180 --> 00:01:29,480
1944, December.

9
00:01:29,520 --> 00:01:30,640
I was miles
from the front...

10
00:01:30,680 --> 00:01:32,310
and a stranger to war.

11
00:01:32,350 --> 00:01:33,980
Troops, fuel dumps...

12
00:01:34,020 --> 00:01:35,150
enemy units...

13
00:01:35,190 --> 00:01:37,160
they were pins
on a map to me.

14
00:01:37,190 --> 00:01:38,350
Champagne?

15
00:01:39,360 --> 00:01:40,830
Are you trying
to score a few points?

16
00:01:40,860 --> 00:01:42,990
Just trying to aid
the war effort, Hart.

17
00:01:43,030 --> 00:01:44,160
Tom.

18
00:01:44,200 --> 00:01:45,320
Sir.

19
00:01:45,370 --> 00:01:46,660
The captain needs a lift
back to the 106th.

20
00:01:46,700 --> 00:01:48,170
Can you find him a driver?

21
00:01:48,200 --> 00:01:50,000
I can take him, sir.

22
00:01:50,040 --> 00:01:51,660
Funny. I had a feeling
you'd say that.

23
00:01:51,710 --> 00:01:53,670
Well, there hasn't been
much movement today, sir.

24
00:01:53,710 --> 00:01:55,500
So I see. Captain.

25
00:01:55,540 --> 00:01:56,670
Oh, don't forget, sir.

26
00:01:56,710 --> 00:01:58,230
You wanted to send some of that
champagne along as well.

27
00:02:00,380 --> 00:02:01,510
Yes.

28
00:02:01,550 --> 00:02:03,480
Yes, thank you
for reminding me, Tom.

29
00:02:04,650 --> 00:02:06,140
The general should get
a kick out of that.

30
00:02:07,500 --> 00:02:08,620
Colonel.

31
00:02:08,670 --> 00:02:09,790
Troops are now fighting...

32
00:02:09,830 --> 00:02:13,460
along a battle line
of 300 miles in Poland...

33
00:02:13,500 --> 00:02:15,470
France, and Germany.

34
00:02:15,510 --> 00:02:17,970
Within 10 weeks
after the first landings

35
00:02:18,010 --> 00:02:20,310
in France last June,

36
00:02:20,340 --> 00:02:24,470
the Allies have landed
nearly 2 million men.

37
00:02:32,020 --> 00:02:33,650
You know what
this army could use, sir?

38
00:02:33,690 --> 00:02:34,990
Snowplow services.

39
00:02:35,030 --> 00:02:36,150
What we could use...

40
00:02:36,190 --> 00:02:37,490
is half a million gallons
of gasoline...

41
00:02:37,530 --> 00:02:38,830
and a road
that wasn't paved...

42
00:02:38,860 --> 00:02:40,020
for Bouncing Betties.

43
00:02:42,200 --> 00:02:43,670
German S-mines.

44
00:02:43,700 --> 00:02:44,860
Yes, sir.

45
00:02:45,700 --> 00:02:47,000
You really ought
to spend a night...

46
00:02:47,040 --> 00:02:48,200
on the line sometime,
Lieutenant.

47
00:02:49,710 --> 00:02:51,170
I know that, sir.

48
00:02:51,210 --> 00:02:53,840
Of course,
it's not too likely, is it?

49
00:02:53,880 --> 00:02:55,040
Sir?

50
00:02:56,050 --> 00:02:58,170
The Colonel says
your father is a senator.

51
00:02:58,220 --> 00:02:59,680
So I guess you won't
spend too many nights...

52
00:02:59,720 --> 00:03:01,210
in a foxhole, will you?

53
00:03:03,660 --> 00:03:05,630
It's nothing
to be ashamed of, son.

54
00:03:05,670 --> 00:03:07,500
That's a hell
of a father to have.

55
00:03:31,360 --> 00:03:33,020
-Where to, sir?
-St. Vith.

56
00:03:34,190 --> 00:03:36,160
I'm afraid you've gone
the wrong way, sir.

57
00:03:36,200 --> 00:03:37,530
St. Vith is due west.

58
00:03:39,870 --> 00:03:42,530
I'm pretty sure
St. Vith is due east.

59
00:03:43,700 --> 00:03:45,540
Sergeant,
it's straight ahead.

60
00:03:46,370 --> 00:03:47,530
Can I see that, sir?

61
00:03:54,210 --> 00:03:56,840
I drove this route
yesterday, Sergeant.

62
00:03:56,880 --> 00:03:58,050
Mm-hmm.

63
00:04:07,840 --> 00:04:09,000
Get your hands up.

64
00:04:10,510 --> 00:04:11,670
Out!

65
00:04:32,700 --> 00:04:33,860
Halt!

66
00:06:15,820 --> 00:06:17,150
Are you in great pain?

67
00:06:18,660 --> 00:06:20,280
First Lieutenant...

68
00:06:20,320 --> 00:06:22,120
Thomas Hart.

69
00:06:22,160 --> 00:06:23,320
Serial number...

70
00:06:24,660 --> 00:06:28,150
1841287.

71
00:06:31,340 --> 00:06:32,670
Would you care
for a cigarette?

72
00:06:35,170 --> 00:06:37,660
Your train is
an 8 kilometer march from here.

73
00:06:38,680 --> 00:06:40,470
Of course,
with some shoes on...

74
00:06:40,510 --> 00:06:41,670
you might be all right.

75
00:06:43,680 --> 00:06:45,490
First Lieutenant...

76
00:06:45,530 --> 00:06:46,690
Thomas Hart.

77
00:06:48,030 --> 00:06:52,020
Serial number 1841287.

78
00:06:53,030 --> 00:06:54,660
Thank you, Lieutenant.

79
00:06:54,700 --> 00:06:56,330
But we both know...

80
00:06:56,370 --> 00:06:58,200
there is much more
to you than that.

81
00:07:04,650 --> 00:07:06,980
Show me locations
of the fuel dumps.

82
00:07:08,980 --> 00:07:10,610
Just point...

83
00:07:10,650 --> 00:07:11,980
and we can end all this.

84
00:07:36,080 --> 00:07:37,840
I'll have your clothes
returned to you immediately.

85
00:07:38,850 --> 00:07:40,510
When you are dressed,
we'll have another chat.

86
00:07:41,360 --> 00:07:42,520
Our last one, I hope.

87
00:08:04,320 --> 00:08:05,610
Smile, Joe.

88
00:08:05,650 --> 00:08:07,080
For you the war is over.

89
00:08:49,370 --> 00:08:50,360
Lieutenant.

90
00:08:51,210 --> 00:08:52,540
This will help
against the cold.

91
00:08:54,040 --> 00:08:55,670
No thanks, soldier.

92
00:08:55,710 --> 00:08:56,840
I'll be all right.

93
00:08:56,880 --> 00:08:58,000
No, you won't.

94
00:08:58,050 --> 00:08:59,170
Come on. Take it.

95
00:08:59,210 --> 00:09:00,680
Just till you warm up.

96
00:09:00,720 --> 00:09:01,840
Take it, sir.

97
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:22,130
Hey, Captain...

98
00:09:22,170 --> 00:09:24,970
does somebody tell our folks
about us being captured?

99
00:09:25,010 --> 00:09:26,630
Germans give a list
to the military...

100
00:09:26,670 --> 00:09:28,800
and the military
notifies the family.

101
00:09:28,840 --> 00:09:30,170
Is that voluntary, sir?

102
00:09:31,510 --> 00:09:32,820
How do you mean,
Lieutenant?

103
00:09:32,860 --> 00:09:34,650
Uh, I mean...

104
00:09:34,690 --> 00:09:36,020
can you ask them not to?

105
00:09:38,530 --> 00:09:39,690
I don't think so.

106
00:10:07,060 --> 00:10:08,890
Have to put
some straw in there.

107
00:10:10,390 --> 00:10:13,190
Straw in your shoes...

108
00:10:13,230 --> 00:10:14,390
for frostbite.

109
00:10:44,930 --> 00:10:46,220
Another slave detail, sir.

110
00:10:48,760 --> 00:10:50,060
Hey, ladies...

111
00:10:50,100 --> 00:10:51,560
next batch of shells
you turn out...

112
00:10:51,600 --> 00:10:53,730
nothing but duds
this time, all right?

113
00:10:53,770 --> 00:10:55,600
Mortars no boom boom, ja?

114
00:11:00,440 --> 00:11:01,570
Fire!

115
00:11:01,610 --> 00:11:03,670
Captain, P-51 incoming.

116
00:11:03,710 --> 00:11:05,010
-Incoming!
-Ours?

117
00:11:05,050 --> 00:11:06,170
Get down, everybody!

118
00:11:06,210 --> 00:11:07,370
Get down!

119
00:11:16,720 --> 00:11:18,450
Everybody stay down!

120
00:11:18,490 --> 00:11:19,650
Keep low!

121
00:11:24,580 --> 00:11:25,870
Captain, what's happening?

122
00:11:25,910 --> 00:11:27,040
Why are they
shooting at us?

123
00:11:27,080 --> 00:11:28,240
They can't read the roof.

124
00:11:32,750 --> 00:11:34,380
All right, get the doors!

125
00:11:34,420 --> 00:11:36,720
Everybody get the doors!

126
00:11:36,750 --> 00:11:37,910
Come on, now!

127
00:11:38,760 --> 00:11:39,920
Get down!

128
00:11:44,830 --> 00:11:46,130
Get down! Down!

129
00:11:50,100 --> 00:11:51,260
Hart, help out!

130
00:11:59,340 --> 00:12:00,970
-Come on!
-Go! Go! Go!

131
00:12:17,730 --> 00:12:19,400
Go on, now!
Let's go!

132
00:12:21,580 --> 00:12:22,700
Moving out!

133
00:12:22,740 --> 00:12:24,510
Get the other cars!

134
00:12:29,580 --> 00:12:31,050
Get the other cars!

135
00:12:31,080 --> 00:12:32,380
Let's go! Now!

136
00:12:32,420 --> 00:12:34,150
We're spelling out!

137
00:12:34,190 --> 00:12:36,380
Round up your men now!

138
00:12:36,420 --> 00:12:38,390
We're spelling out
our position!

139
00:12:38,430 --> 00:12:39,590
We're spelling out!

140
00:12:40,430 --> 00:12:43,060
Hart, get that man
clear of here.

141
00:12:43,100 --> 00:12:44,720
Let's get in line!

142
00:12:44,770 --> 00:12:46,230
Assemble on me!

143
00:12:46,270 --> 00:12:48,330
-Assemble!
-Move it! Move it!

144
00:12:58,610 --> 00:12:59,910
All right, men!

145
00:12:59,950 --> 00:13:01,470
Let's get back in line!

146
00:13:02,050 --> 00:13:03,040
Move it!

147
00:13:27,620 --> 00:13:30,020
It's not helping.

148
00:13:31,090 --> 00:13:32,250
Come on, men!

149
00:14:00,020 --> 00:14:01,190
Oh, Christ.

150
00:14:01,330 --> 00:14:02,290
Are you OK?

151
00:14:02,330 --> 00:14:03,950
Keep looking at me.
Look at me.

152
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:05,160
Look at me.

153
00:14:06,430 --> 00:14:08,090
Oh, shit. Shit.

154
00:14:08,130 --> 00:14:10,510
All right.
Are you all right?

155
00:14:34,040 --> 00:14:35,370
They're telling us to march.

156
00:14:36,370 --> 00:14:38,240
Probably ought to take
his boots, Lieutenant.

157
00:14:40,540 --> 00:14:41,840
Lieutenant!

158
00:14:41,880 --> 00:14:43,840
Take his boots.

159
00:14:43,880 --> 00:14:45,680
'Cause either you
or some Jerry's gonna get 'em.

160
00:14:45,710 --> 00:14:46,840
Take 'em, sir...

161
00:14:46,880 --> 00:14:48,540
while you still got feet
to put 'em on.

162
00:14:49,880 --> 00:14:51,010
His socks, too.

163
00:14:51,050 --> 00:14:52,380
Ain't gonna help him any.

164
00:14:53,220 --> 00:14:54,380
Stay together.

165
00:14:56,890 --> 00:14:58,050
All right.

166
00:17:09,850 --> 00:17:11,010
Once again...

167
00:17:12,520 --> 00:17:17,690
I'm forced to remind you
escape is not a sport.

168
00:17:28,540 --> 00:17:29,700
Think of it this way.

169
00:17:30,880 --> 00:17:32,840
Now these Russians
have a chance...

170
00:17:32,880 --> 00:17:34,370
at a happy new year.

171
00:17:50,560 --> 00:17:52,550
Those are dogs
you're saluting, Colonel.

172
00:17:54,080 --> 00:17:55,240
Animals.

173
00:17:59,080 --> 00:18:00,210
My country doesn't make...

174
00:18:00,250 --> 00:18:01,720
those kinds of
distinctions, Colonel.

175
00:18:14,700 --> 00:18:16,030
They're our allies, Colonel.

176
00:18:17,030 --> 00:18:19,520
Oh, yes.
You and your allies.

177
00:18:20,870 --> 00:18:23,700
Let me tell you
about you and your allies.

178
00:18:27,540 --> 00:18:31,170
The Ministry of War
has just released the figures...

179
00:18:31,210 --> 00:18:32,870
from our offensive
in the Ardennes.

180
00:18:34,050 --> 00:18:37,350
Two hundred thousand Allies
killed or captured.

181
00:18:37,390 --> 00:18:38,510
Your Third Army--

182
00:18:38,550 --> 00:18:40,680
Patton--
in full retreat.

183
00:18:40,720 --> 00:18:44,180
And the wehrmacht has captured
enough abundant fuel...

184
00:18:44,230 --> 00:18:45,520
to retake Paris--

185
00:18:45,560 --> 00:18:48,050
perhaps even drive
your troops back to the sea.

186
00:18:49,410 --> 00:18:52,240
Might be a bit crowded
around here this winter.

187
00:19:08,360 --> 00:19:09,490
Turn around, Joes.

188
00:19:09,530 --> 00:19:11,620
Yes. Turn around.

189
00:19:19,870 --> 00:19:21,360
Ross. Hart.

190
00:19:23,210 --> 00:19:25,000
Ross and Hart.

191
00:19:25,040 --> 00:19:26,200
I'm Captain Ross.

192
00:19:27,550 --> 00:19:28,840
Major Clary.

193
00:19:28,880 --> 00:19:30,010
Lieutenant Hart.

194
00:19:30,050 --> 00:19:31,850
Lieutenant.

195
00:19:31,880 --> 00:19:33,350
Debriefing, gentleman.
Officer's hut.

196
00:19:33,380 --> 00:19:35,110
On the double.

197
00:19:35,150 --> 00:19:37,090
The German counterattack on
the American Third Army front...

198
00:19:37,090 --> 00:19:37,680
The German counterattack on
the American Third Army front...

199
00:19:37,720 --> 00:19:38,850
is still going on.

200
00:19:38,890 --> 00:19:40,020
The entire front...

201
00:19:40,060 --> 00:19:42,190
stretching about
30 miles south of Monschau...

202
00:19:42,230 --> 00:19:43,350
is in full view.

203
00:19:43,390 --> 00:19:45,700
On our side,
countermeasures are being taken.

204
00:19:45,740 --> 00:19:49,040
On the enemy's side,
more strafes are being flown in.

205
00:19:49,080 --> 00:19:51,380
This is a major German effort.

206
00:19:51,410 --> 00:19:53,040
Some of the best units
in the German army...

207
00:19:53,080 --> 00:19:54,570
were involved
in this penetration.

208
00:19:56,080 --> 00:19:57,210
At ease, soldier.

209
00:19:57,250 --> 00:19:58,410
Sit down.

210
00:20:02,590 --> 00:20:03,750
Thank you, sir.

211
00:20:07,600 --> 00:20:08,930
So tell me, Lieutenant...

212
00:20:10,770 --> 00:20:11,930
How come you're not dead?

213
00:20:12,770 --> 00:20:13,930
Sir?

214
00:20:15,440 --> 00:20:17,060
First you survive
crashing that jeep...

215
00:20:17,110 --> 00:20:19,230
then Hans and Fritz
take your boots.

216
00:20:19,270 --> 00:20:21,100
You got a rabbit's foot
in your pocket, son?

217
00:20:22,940 --> 00:20:25,240
Two horseshoes
and a 4-leaf clover, sir.

218
00:20:25,280 --> 00:20:26,440
Atta boy.

219
00:20:27,450 --> 00:20:28,570
By the way...

220
00:20:28,620 --> 00:20:29,950
you might want to take it easy
on that bread.

221
00:20:30,950 --> 00:20:33,420
You haven't had anything
solid for a while.

222
00:20:33,450 --> 00:20:35,580
Wouldn't want you to wind up
in the infirmary.

223
00:20:35,620 --> 00:20:36,780
I don't know, sir.

224
00:20:37,960 --> 00:20:39,930
After the march I just made...

225
00:20:39,970 --> 00:20:42,300
and infirmary might look
like the Waldorf to me.

226
00:20:45,810 --> 00:20:47,970
A stomach can shrink
quite a bit in 17 days.

227
00:20:49,310 --> 00:20:50,940
That's the number, isn't it?

228
00:20:50,980 --> 00:20:52,450
Seventeen days?

229
00:20:52,480 --> 00:20:54,280
Six days on the train...

230
00:20:54,320 --> 00:20:56,120
another 6 days of marching.

231
00:20:56,150 --> 00:20:57,620
What was it, Joe?

232
00:20:57,660 --> 00:20:58,820
Five days of interrogation?

233
00:20:59,660 --> 00:21:00,820
No, sir.

234
00:21:04,260 --> 00:21:05,420
Three days.

235
00:21:08,430 --> 00:21:11,420
Well, anyway...
easy does it.

236
00:21:12,770 --> 00:21:14,430
Yes, sir. Thank you.

237
00:21:15,610 --> 00:21:17,730
So this interrogator
they threw at you...

238
00:21:17,780 --> 00:21:19,110
his name wasn't Schumann,
was it?

239
00:21:24,950 --> 00:21:26,110
No, sir.

240
00:21:27,450 --> 00:21:28,610
Lutz.

241
00:21:32,290 --> 00:21:33,950
Schumann was a real prick.

242
00:21:34,790 --> 00:21:36,130
Almost broke me in two.

243
00:22:00,530 --> 00:22:02,360
Not much for small talk,
I guess.

244
00:22:02,400 --> 00:22:04,300
You come to appreciate that.

245
00:22:09,070 --> 00:22:10,230
Smoke, Lieutenant?

246
00:22:12,080 --> 00:22:13,410
Would you care
for a cigarette?

247
00:22:14,910 --> 00:22:17,400
Again, Lieutenant,
I need to ask you...

248
00:22:18,250 --> 00:22:19,410
the fuel dumps...

249
00:22:22,750 --> 00:22:23,910
Thank you.

250
00:22:27,090 --> 00:22:28,890
This Captain Lutz...

251
00:22:28,930 --> 00:22:31,090
he know much about
your operations at the chateau?

252
00:22:33,940 --> 00:22:35,100
He knew everything, sir.

253
00:22:36,440 --> 00:22:38,070
Fuel dump locations?

254
00:22:38,110 --> 00:22:39,270
Troop movements?

255
00:22:42,120 --> 00:22:43,740
Sir, he knew what
I'd had for breakfast...

256
00:22:43,780 --> 00:22:45,080
the morning of my capture.

257
00:22:52,290 --> 00:22:54,950
Point,
and we can end all this.

258
00:23:00,470 --> 00:23:02,900
Just name, rank,
and serial number.

259
00:23:07,410 --> 00:23:08,570
Good enough.

260
00:23:10,080 --> 00:23:11,240
You're excused, Lieutenant.

261
00:23:12,580 --> 00:23:13,880
Unfortunately,
we won't be able...

262
00:23:13,910 --> 00:23:15,040
to quarter you here.

263
00:23:15,080 --> 00:23:16,210
We're full up.

264
00:23:16,250 --> 00:23:17,810
We're gonna have to
put you in Barracks 27.

265
00:23:20,090 --> 00:23:22,560
Isn't barracks 27
for enlisted men, sir?

266
00:23:22,590 --> 00:23:23,720
Yes, it is...

267
00:23:23,760 --> 00:23:24,880
but as you can see...

268
00:23:24,930 --> 00:23:27,100
the Germans are doing a rather
brisk business these days.

269
00:23:28,110 --> 00:23:29,270
You'll be comfortable there.

270
00:23:30,440 --> 00:23:31,600
Sir.

271
00:23:35,950 --> 00:23:37,780
-Lieutenant.
-Sir.

272
00:24:15,920 --> 00:24:17,080
Point.

273
00:24:22,590 --> 00:24:24,400
Point or say
hello to stumps...

274
00:24:24,440 --> 00:24:25,600
for the rest
of your life.

275
00:24:37,450 --> 00:24:38,610
Good.

